President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed May 6, 2021, as a National Day of Prayer in the United States. In his proclamation, he highlights the importance of prayer throughout American history, mentioning its role in providing strength, hope, and guidance, as well as its contribution to moral movements. The First Amendment of the Constitution protects the rights of free speech and religious liberty, including the right to pray. President Biden acknowledges the challenges faced by the nation, such as the COVID-19 pandemic, racial justice issues, and climate change, and emphasizes that prayer can provide hope and unity in addressing these challenges. He quotes the late Congressman John Lewis, who believed in the power of committed and determined people to make a difference. The proclamation calls for unity and a recommitment to the core freedoms that define the nation, celebrating the ability to exercise convictions freely. President Biden invites citizens to give thanks according to their own faiths and consciences and joins people of faith in prayers for spiritual guidance, mercy, and protection.